rr[i + 1] > ... > arr[arr.length - 1]\n\n\n\n\n \nExample 1:\nInput: arr = [2,1]\nOutput: false\nExample 2:\nInput: arr = [3,5,5]\nOutput: false\nExample 3:\nInput: arr = [0,3,2,1]\nOutput: true\n\n \nConstraints:\n\n1 <= arr.length <= 104\n0 <= arr[i] <= 104\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def validMountainArray(self, arr: List[int]) -> bool:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def validMountainArray(self, arr: List[int]) -> bool:\n        n = len(arr)\n        if n < 3:\n            return False\n        \n        i = 0\n        \n        # Walk up\n        while i + 1 < n and arr[i] < arr[i + 1]:\n            i += 1\n        \n        # Peak can't be first or last\n        if i == 0 or i == n - 1:\n            return False\n        \n        # Walk down\n        while i + 1 < n and arr[i] > arr[i + 1]:\n            i += 1\n        \n        return i == n - 1\n```\n\nThis solution first checks if the array length is less than 3, in which case it immediately returns `False` because a mountain array must have at least three elements. It then walks up the mountain by incrementing the index `i` while the current element is less than the next one. If `i` reaches the end of the array or does not move beyond the first element, it returns `False` because a valid peak must exist. Finally, it walks down the mountain and checks if it reaches the end of the array, confirming that the array is a valid mountain array.", "estimated_date": 1542499200000}